ntry. Locating Shahid in a diasporic space of exile, the volume traces the poet's transnationalist attempts to bridge East and West and his movement toward a true internationalism. In addition to offering close formal analyses of most of Shahid's poems and poetry collections, the contributors also situate him in relation to both Western and subcontinental poetic forms, particularly the ghazal. Many also offer personal anecdotes that convey the milieu in which the poet lived and wrote, as well as his personal preoccupations. The book concludes with the poet's 1997 interview with Suvir Kaul, which appears in print here for the first time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors, KashmirixCriticism and interpretation. 4aAmerican Studies : Asian American Studies. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aAli, Kazim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalakian, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Vedatrayee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakraborty, Abin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Sinchan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Sisir Kumar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Sisir Kumar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEspada, Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhosh, Tapan Kumar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 